{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516488"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:43:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:43:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12636"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12636"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.68,0.04,0.1,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5117"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55427"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5117"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12636"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40963"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"4051"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8580"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9328"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10151"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13662"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16166"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42789"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55427","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55427"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn unidentifiable man with substantial lacerations to his arms and legs is brought into a trauma centre by the emergency retrieval service after being called to the site of an altercation. No alcohol or illicit substances are found nearby. The paramedics decided to \u0027scoop and run\u0027 as the emergency department is only a couple of minutes away.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EOn arrival assessment, the patient is in a pool of blood and appears drowsy, unable to complete full sentences. The peripheries are cold and clammy whilst central capillary refill time is 4.5 seconds. The radial pulse is thready and rapid. His pupils are equal and reactive bilaterally. On removal of his clothing, there is a long laceration in his left popliteal fossa which is haemorrhaging a large volume of bright red blood. Direct bleed site pressure is unable to contain the bleeding.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EVital signs: respiration rate 28/min, temperature 36.5\u00b0C, heart rate 124/min, blood pressure 82/51 mmHg, oxygen saturation 95%.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next intervention?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["500ml bolus of 0.9% NaCl","Mid thigh tourniquet","Non-rebreather mask at 15L","One unit of O negative packed red blood cells","Administer a 1g bolus of tranexamic acid (TXA)"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has sustained major trauma and is now experiencing a major haemorrhage of his distal extremity, with concurrent peripheral signs of slow capillary refill time, clammy extremities and thready rapid radial pulse indicating low blood pressure and perfusion. Controlling the bleed is therefore the most important and life-saving action that needs to be taken in this situation. As a result, direct bleed site pressure is the most important and effective initial intervention for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDefining a bleed into compressible and non-compressible determines the order, importance and the speed of interventions necessary. Compressible bleeds are usually those found on the extremities, whilst non-compressible bleeds tend to occur in truncal lesions. Given the bleed site is visualisable and is on the extremity, this is a compressible bleed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDirect pressure remains the most effective initial intervention for compressible lesions, and is usually in the form of digital pressure. Other pressure interventions can include gauze pressure (often soaked in adrenaline) or bandages. Given that direct pressure has failed, \u003Cstrong\u003Eapplying a mid thigh tourniquet\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step of action to control the bleeding. Ideally applying tourniquet at a location reasonably proximal to the point of the bleed as we want to minimise as much as possible to control the haemorrhage whilst maintaining reasonable perfusion to the rest of the unaffected sites.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E500ml bolus of 0.9% NaCl\u003C/strong\u003E, or a different crystalloid fluid, is not the first line management. Although fluid resuscitation will cause rapid volume expansion to help correct low blood pressure, crystalloids are only encouraged if there are no blood products available.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETransfusing\u003Cstrong\u003E one unit of O negative packed red blood cells\u003C/strong\u003E would be an important intervention for this patient, however stopping the source of the bleed would take priority to prevent further blood loss. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-rebreather mask at 15L\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate next step in intervention as the \u003Cstrong\u003Eimmediate management\u003C/strong\u003E of a major trauma patient should follow a\u003Cstrong\u003E ABCDE\u003C/strong\u003E approach. for \u003Cstrong\u003ECatastrophic haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E. Identify any large volume bleeding and look for any high volume blood loss. If there is any large volume bleeding, immediate actions (direct pressure, tourniquet) should be taken. After the bleeding is under control, check for patient\u0027s O2 saturation. If the patient has poor O2 sats, then oxygen should be administered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETranexamic acid (TXA)\u003C/strong\u003E is a clot stabiliser. It can be used in a trauma setting but it is not the most appropriate next step management. TXA has shown positive results in the short-term, but 30 day mortality is not significantly different from usual interventions. TXA is proven to safely reduce the risk of death in bleeding trauma patients in a randomised-controlled trial consisting of a large sample size of 20,127 patients in 274 hospitals in 40 countries.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Immediate management of a major trauma patient should follow a \u003CC\u003EABCDE approach"],"references":["Donley ER, Munakomi S, Loyd JW. Hemorrhage Control. [Updated 2022 Nov 16]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK535393/","Effects of tranexamic acid on death, vascular occlusive events, and blood transfusion in trauma patients with significant haemorrhage (CRASH-2): A randomised, placebo-controlled trial. The Lancet. 2010 Jun 15;376(9734):23\u201332. doi:10.1016/s0140-6736(10)60835-5","Prehospital tranexamic acid for severe trauma. New England Journal of Medicine. 2023 Jul 13;389(2):127\u201336. doi:10.1056/nejmoa2215457","Rossaint, R., Afshari, A., Bouillon, B. et al. The European guideline on management of major bleeding and coagulopathy following trauma: sixth edition. Crit Care 27, 80 (2023). https://doi.org/10.1186/s13054-023-04327-7"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40963"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12636"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40963","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40963"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-15T15:17:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-15T15:18:47+10:30"},"relationships":